  "intros": "<div class=\"tabs-container\">\n    <h2 class=\"text-3xl font-extrabold text-gray-800 mb-6 mt-6 text-center\">Lesson 11: Representing √x Geometrically on the Number Line</h2>\n    <p class=\"text-gray-600 text-lg mb-8 text-center px-4\">We found √2 and √3. But what about √3.5 or √9.3? There's a beautiful geometric trick to find the square root of ANY positive number!</p>\n\n    <!-- Hidden radio buttons that control the state of the tabs -->\n    <input type=\"radio\" id=\"tab1\" name=\"tabs\" checked>\n    <input type=\"radio\" id=\"tab2\" name=\"tabs\">\n    <input type=\"radio\" id=\"tab3\" name=\"tabs\">\n    <input type=\"radio\" id=\"tab4\" name=\"tabs\">\n    <input type=\"radio\" id=\"tab5\" name=\"tabs\">\n\n    <!-- Tab Header Buttons (styled labels) -->\n    <div class=\"tabs-header flex flex-row bg-gray-50 border-b border-gray-200 text-sm font-medium text-center text-gray-600 rounded-t-lg overflow-hidden\">\n        <label for=\"tab1\" class=\"tab-label\" id=\"label1\" title=\"Intro 1: The Semicircle Secret\">1</label>\n        <label for=\"tab2\" class=\"tab-label\" id=\"label2\" title=\"Intro 2: The Balancing Act\">2</label>\n        <label for=\"tab3\" class=\"tab-label\" id=\"label3\" title=\"Intro 3: The Geometric Mean Machine\">3</label>\n        <label for=\"tab4\" class=\"tab-label\" id=\"label4\" title=\"Intro 4: A New Kind of Ruler\">4</label>\n        <label for=\"tab5\" class=\"tab-label\" id=\"label5\" title=\"Intro 5: Beyond the Spiral\">5</label>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Tab Content Panels -->\n    <div class=\"tab-content-container p-6 sm:p-8\">\n        <!-- Tab 1 Content: The Semicircle Secret -->\n        <div class=\"tab-content content1\" id=\"content1\">\n            <h3 class=\"intro-title text-xl font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-3\">Intro 1: The Semicircle Secret</h3>\n            <h2 class=\"intro-question text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4\">Did you know that a simple semicircle holds the secret to finding the square root of any number?</h2>\n            <div class=\"description-container flex flex-col justify-center items-center w-full mb-6 p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg shadow-inner\">\n                <svg viewBox=\"0 0 1600 900\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" class=\"w-full max-w-3xl rounded-md\">\n                    <rect width=\"1600\" height=\"900\" fill=\"#ffffff\"/>\n                    <!-- Base line -->\n                    <line x1=\"200\" y1=\"600\" x2=\"1400\" y2=\"600\" stroke=\"#4c566a\" stroke-width=\"6\"/>\n                    <text x=\"550\" y=\"650\" font-size=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\">A number 'x'</text>\n                    <text x=\"1250\" y=\"650\" font-size=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\">1</text>\n                    \n                    <!-- Semicircle -->\n                    <path d=\"M200 600 A 600 600 0 0 1 1400 600\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#88c0d0\" stroke-width=\"8\" stroke-dasharray=\"20 10\"/>\n                    \n                    <!-- Perpendicular line -->\n                    <line x1=\"900\" y1=\"600\" x2=\"900\" y2=\"246\" stroke=\"#bf616a\" stroke-width=\"10\"/>\n                     <text x=\"950\" y=\"450\" font-size=\"80\" text-anchor=\"start\" fill=\"#bf616a\">√x</text>\n                     <text x=\"800\" y=\"150\" font-size=\"60\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#2e3440\">This magic line has a length of √x !</text>\n                </svg>\n                <p class=\"intro-explanation text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mt-4\">We've used right-angled triangles to find square roots like √2 and √5. But what about a number like √7.5? Trying to find two sides 'a' and 'b' such that a² + b² = 7.5 is very difficult. Luckily, there's a much more elegant and universal method that works for ANY positive number, 'x'. The secret lies in the properties of a semicircle. By cleverly constructing a line segment with a length of 'x + 1' and making that the diameter of a semicircle, we can create a magic point. A perpendicular line drawn from the 'x' mark up to the edge of the semicircle will have a length of exactly √x. This beautiful geometric proof allows us to construct the square root of any number we can imagine, no matter how \"messy\" it seems.</p>\n                <p class=\"intro-tagline mt-6 text-center font-semibold text-sky-600 italic\">The semicircle: A perfect calculator for finding any square root.</p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n\n        <!-- Tab 2 Content: The Balancing Act -->\n        <div class=\"tab-content content2\" id=\"content2\">\n            <h3 class=\"intro-title text-xl font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-3\">Intro 2: The Balancing Act</h3>\n            <h2 class=\"intro-question text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4\">Imagine a see-saw with a length of 'x' on one side and '1' on the other. Where is the \"balance point\" that reveals the square root?</h2>\n            <div class=\"description-container flex flex-col justify-center items-center w-full mb-6 p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg shadow-inner\">\n                 <svg viewBox=\"0 0 1600 900\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" class=\"w-full max-w-3xl rounded-md\">\n                    <rect width=\"1600\" height=\"900\" fill=\"#ffffff\"/>\n\n                     <!-- Base line -->\n                    <line x1=\"200\" y1=\"600\" x2=\"1400\" y2=\"600\" stroke=\"#4c566a\" stroke-width=\"10\"/>\n                    <text x=\"250\" y=\"580\" font-size=\"50\" text-anchor=\"start\">A</text>\n                    <text x=\"900\" y=\"580\" font-size=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\">B</text>\n                    <text x=\"1000\" y=\"580\" font-size=\"50\" text-anchor=\"start\">C</text>\n                    <rect x=\"250\" y=\"610\" width=\"650\" height=\"20\" fill=\"#a3be8c\"/>\n                    <text x=\"575\" y=\"660\" font-size=\"40\" text-anchor=\"middle\">Length 'x'</text>\n                    <rect x=\"900\" y=\"610\" width=\"100\" height=\"20\" fill=\"#bf616a\"/>\n                    <text x=\"950\" y=\"660\" font-size=\"40\" text-anchor=\"middle\">Length '1'</text>\n\n                    <!-- Semicircle -->\n                    <path d=\"M250 600 A 425 425 0 0 1 1100 600\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#d8dee9\" stroke-width=\"6\"/>\n                    <circle cx=\"675\" cy=\"600\" r=\"10\" fill=\"#4c566a\"/><text x=\"675\" y=\"580\" font-size=\"40\">Midpoint O</text>\n                    \n                    <!-- Balancing line -->\n                    <line x1=\"900\" y1=\"600\" x2=\"675\" y2=\"280\" stroke=\"#88c0d0\" stroke-width=\"8\"/>\n                    <line x1=\"675\" y1=\"280\" x2=\"900\" y2=\"180\" stroke=\"#88c0d0\" stroke-width=\"8\"/>\n                     <text x=\"800\" y=\"250\" font-size=\"60\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#88c0d0\">√x</text>\n                 </svg>\n                 <p class=\"intro-explanation text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mt-4\">The square root spiral method for finding √x can get very complicated for large or decimal values of x. We need a more general approach. Think of it like a balancing act. We create a long line segment by placing our desired number, 'x', next to a segment of length '1'. The total length is x+1. The key is to find the midpoint of this entire segment and use it as the center to draw a semicircle over the line. Now, from the point where 'x' and '1' meet, we draw a vertical line straight up. The length of this vertical line, our \"balancing pole,\" is guaranteed by the properties of circles and triangles to be exactly √x. It's a clever construction that balances the lengths of 'x' and '1' to produce their geometric mean: the square root.</p>\n                 <p class=\"intro-tagline mt-6 text-center font-semibold text-sky-600 italic\">Balancing 'x' and '1' on a semicircle reveals √x.</p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n\n        <!-- Tab 3 Content: The Geometric Mean Machine -->\n        <div class=\"tab-content content3\" id=\"content3\">\n            <h3 class=\"intro-title text-xl font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-3\">Intro 3: The Geometric Mean Machine</h3>\n            <h2 class=\"intro-question text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4\">How can we build a simple \"machine\" out of lines and circles that takes in a number 'x' and outputs its square root?</h2>\n            <div class=\"description-container flex flex-col justify-center items-center w-full mb-6 p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg shadow-inner\">\n                <svg viewBox=\"0 0 1600 900\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" class=\"w-full max-w-3xl rounded-md\">\n                    <rect width=\"1600\" height=\"900\" fill=\"#ffffff\"/>\n                    \n                    <!-- Machine -->\n                    <rect x=\"100\" y=\"200\" width=\"1400\" height=\"600\" fill=\"#eceff4\" rx=\"30\" stroke=\"#4c566a\" stroke-width=\"8\"/>\n                    <text x=\"800\" y=\"150\" font-family=\"sans-serif\" font-size=\"60\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#2e3440\">The √x Machine</text>\n\n                    <!-- Input -->\n                    <rect x=\"200\" y=\"300\" width=\"600\" height=\"100\" fill=\"#a3be8c\" rx=\"10\"/>\n                    <text x=\"500\" y=\"365\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\">INPUT: Length 'x'</text>\n                    \n                    <!-- Process -->\n                    <g transform=\"translate(0, 100)\">\n                        <line x1=\"200\" y1=\"500\" x2=\"800\" y2=\"500\" stroke=\"#4c566a\" stroke-width=\"6\"/>\n                        <text x=\"500\" y=\"480\">Place 'x' next to '1'</text>\n                        <line x1=\"800\" y1=\"500\" x2=\"900\" y2=\"500\" stroke=\"#bf616a\" stroke-width=\"6\"/>\n                        <path d=\"M200 500 A 350 350 0 0 1 900 500\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#88c0d0\" stroke-width=\"4\"/>\n                        <text x=\"550\" y=\"300\">Draw a Semicircle</text>\n                        <line x1=\"800\" y1=\"500\" x2=\"800\" y2=\"345\" stroke=\"#4c566a\" stroke-width=\"6\"/>\n                        <text x=\"830\" y=\"420\">Draw Perpendicular</text>\n                    </g>\n\n                    <!-- Output -->\n                    <rect x=\"1000\" y=\"500\" width=\"400\" height=\"100\" fill=\"#b48ead\" rx=\"10\"/>\n                     <text x=\"1200\" y=\"565\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"white\">OUTPUT: Length √x</text>\n                </svg>\n                <p class=\"intro-explanation text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mt-4\">We're going to build a machine! Not a physical one, but a geometric one. Here's how it works: **Input:** Take any positive length 'x'. **Step 1:** Place this length next to a length of 1, creating a single line segment of length x+1. **Step 2:** Find the middle of this new, long segment and use it as the center to draw a semicircle. **Step 3:** From the point where 'x' and '1' meet, draw a line straight up to the semicircle. **Output:** The length of that vertical line is the output of our machine, and it is always exactly √x. This process is a physical manifestation of a mathematical concept called the \"geometric mean.\" It's a foolproof way to find the square root of any positive number you can draw.</p>\n                <p class=\"intro-tagline mt-6 text-center font-semibold text-sky-600 italic\">A geometric machine for a mathematical solution.</p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n        \n        <!-- Tab 4 Content: A New Kind of Ruler -->\n        <div class=\"tab-content content4\" id=\"content4\">\n            <h3 class=\"intro-title text-xl font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-3\">Intro 4: A New Kind of Ruler</h3>\n            <h2 class=\"intro-question text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4\">Your normal ruler has marks for 1, 2, 3.5, etc. How could you build a special ruler that has a mark for √5.3?</h2>\n            <div class=\"description-container flex flex-col justify-center items-center w-full mb-6 p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg shadow-inner\">\n                <svg viewBox=\"0 0 1600 900\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" class=\"w-full max-w-3xl rounded-md\">\n                    <rect width=\"1600\" height=\"900\" fill=\"#ffffff\"/>\n                    \n                    <!-- Line segment x -->\n                    <line x1=\"200\" y1=\"300\" x2=\"800\" y2=\"300\" stroke=\"#a3be8c\" stroke-width=\"8\"/>\n                    <text x=\"500\" y=\"270\" font-size=\"40\" text-anchor=\"middle\">Step 1: Mark out 5.3</text>\n                    \n                    <!-- Add 1 -->\n                    <line x1=\"800\" y1=\"300\" x2=\"950\" y2=\"300\" stroke=\"#bf616a\" stroke-width=\"8\"/>\n                    <text x=\"875\" y=\"350\" font-size=\"40\" text-anchor=\"middle\">Step 2: Add 1</text>\n                    \n                    <!-- Semicircle -->\n                    <path d=\"M200 300 A 375 375 0 0 1 950 300\" stroke=\"#d8dee9\" stroke-width=\"6\" fill=\"none\"/>\n                    <text x=\"575\" y=\"100\" font-size=\"40\" text-anchor=\"middle\">Step 3: Draw Semicircle</text>\n                    \n                    <!-- Perpendicular -->\n                    <line x1=\"800\" y1=\"300\" x2=\"800\" y2=\"-41\" stroke=\"#88c0d0\" stroke-width=\"8\"/>\n                    <text x=\"900\" y=\"100\" font-size=\"40\" fill=\"#88c0d0\">Step 4: This is length √5.3</text>\n                    \n                    <!-- Final ruler -->\n                     <rect x=\"100\" y=\"700\" width=\"1400\" height=\"100\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#ebcb8b\"/>\n                     <text x=\"800\" y=\"650\" font-size=\"40\" text-anchor=\"middle\">Step 5: Transfer to our ruler</text>\n                     <line x1=\"400\" y1=\"700\" x2=\"400\" y2=\"800\" stroke=\"#4c566a\" stroke-width=\"4\"/><text x=\"400\" y=\"830\" font-size=\"30\">0</text>\n                     <line x1=\"600\" y1=\"700\" x2=\"600\" y2=\"800\" stroke=\"#4c566a\" stroke-width=\"4\"/><text x=\"600\" y=\"830\" font-size=\"30\">1</text>\n                     <line x1=\"800\" y1=\"700\" x2=\"800\" y2=\"800\" stroke=\"#4c566a\" stroke-width=\"4\"/><text x=\"800\" y=\"830\" font-size=\"30\">2</text>\n                     <line x1=\"1000\" y1=\"700\" x2=\"1000\" y2=\"800\" stroke=\"#4c566a\" stroke-width=\"4\"/><text x=\"1000\" y=\"830\" font-size=\"30\">3</text>\n                     <path d=\"M400,700 C600,600 700,600 800, -41\" stroke=\"#88c0d0\" stroke-width=\"4\" fill=\"none\" stroke-dasharray=\"10\"/>\n                     <line x1=\"861\" y1=\"700\" x2=\"861\" y2=\"780\" stroke=\"#bf616a\" stroke-width=\"6\"/>\n                     <text x=\"861\" y=\"810\" font-size=\"30\" text-anchor=\"middle\">√5.3</text>\n\n                </svg>\n                <p class=\"intro-explanation text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mt-4\">Finding the position of an irrational number is like adding a new, custom mark to a ruler. To find √5.3, we can't just estimate. We need to create a physical length of exactly √5.3 to know where to draw our mark. The semicircle method provides the perfect blueprint. We draw a line of length 5.3, add a line of length 1, and use this total length of 6.3 as the diameter for our semicircle. Drawing a perpendicular up from the 5.3 mark gives us our target length of √5.3. Now, we can use a compass to \"pick up\" this length and transfer it onto our number line ruler, starting from 0. The point where the compass lands is the permanent, precise location of √5.3, a mark that no ordinary ruler could ever have.</p>\n                <p class=\"intro-tagline mt-6 text-center font-semibold text-sky-600 italic\">Creating a custom ruler for every irrational number.</p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n\n        <!-- Tab 5 Content: Beyond the Spiral -->\n        <div class=\"tab-content content5\" id=\"content5\">\n            <h3 class=\"intro-title text-xl font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-3\">Intro 5: Beyond the Spiral</h3>\n            <h2 class=\"intro-question text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4\">The square root spiral is great for √2, √3, √4... but what about √4.5? Does the spiral method still work?</h2>\n            <div class=\"description-container flex flex-col justify-center items-center w-full mb-6 p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg shadow-inner\">\n                <svg viewBox=\"0 0 1600 900\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" class=\"w-full max-w-3xl rounded-md\">\n                    <rect width=\"1600\" height=\"900\" fill=\"#ffffff\"/>\n                    <!-- Spiral side -->\n                    <g transform=\"translate(400, 450)\">\n                        <text x=\"0\" y=\"-300\" font-size=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#2e3440\">Spiral Method</text>\n                        <circle cx=\"0\" cy=\"0\" r=\"250\" fill=\"#e5e9f0\"/>\n                        <line x1=\"0\" y1=\"0\" x2=\"100\" y2=\"-100\" stroke=\"#bf616a\" stroke-width=\"4\"/><text x=\"70\" y=\"-30\">√2</text>\n                        <line x1=\"0\" y1=\"0\" x2=\"0\" y2=\"-200\" stroke=\"#d08770\" stroke-width=\"4\"/><text x=\"30\" y=\"-100\">√3</text>\n                        <text x=\"0\" y=\"100\" font-size=\"40\" text-anchor=\"middle\">Good for integers,</text>\n                        <text x=\"0\" y=\"150\" font-size=\"40\" text-anchor=\"middle\">but difficult for decimals!</text>\n                    </g>\n                    <!-- Semicircle side -->\n                     <g transform=\"translate(1200, 450)\">\n                        <text x=\"0\" y=\"-300\" font-size=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#2e3440\">Semicircle Method</text>\n                         <circle cx=\"0\" cy=\"0\" r=\"250\" fill=\"#eceff4\"/>\n                         <path d=\"M-200 0 A 200 200 0 0 1 200 0\" stroke=\"#a3be8c\" stroke-width=\"6\" fill=\"none\"/>\n                         <line x1=\"-200\" y1=\"0\" x2=\"200\" y2=\"0\" stroke=\"#4c566a\" stroke-width=\"4\"/>\n                         <line x1=\"100\" y1=\"0\" x2=\"100\" y2=\"-173\" stroke=\"#bf616a\" stroke-width=\"6\"/>\n                         <text x=\"0\" y=\"100\" font-size=\"40\" text-anchor=\"middle\">Works for ANY</text>\n                        <text x=\"0\" y=\"150\" font-size=\"40\" text-anchor=\"middle\">positive number 'x'!</text>\n                    </g>\n                    \n                    <text x=\"800\" y=\"800\" font-size=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#81a1c1\">A more powerful and general tool.</text>\n                </svg>\n                <p class=\"intro-explanation text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mt-4\">The square root spiral is a clever and beautiful way to find the square roots of whole numbers like √2, √3, etc. But it has a weakness: it relies on the previous step. To find √4.5, you would first need to construct √3.5, which would require √2.5, and so on. This becomes very impractical! We need a more powerful and direct method that doesn't depend on a long chain of previous constructions. The semicircle method is that superior tool. It allows you to find the square root of *any* positive number 'x'—whether it's an integer like 5 or a decimal like 4.5—in a single, self-contained construction. It's the universal key that unlocks the geometric representation for every positive square root, not just the ones in the spiral.</p>\n                <p class=\"intro-tagline mt-6 text-center font-semibold text-sky-600 italic\">The semicircle method: a direct path to the square root of any number.</p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>\n<!--end-of-code-block-->"
